  <title>Logarithms</title>

<activity><title>Solving Equations</title>
<task><p>Compare the two equations below. The first is a quadratic equation, and the second is an exponential equation. You can probably solve both of these equations in your head.
  <me>~~~~\text{(1)}~~~x^2 = 25 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\text{(2)}~~~2^x = 8</me>
Solutions:</p>

<p>Let's analyze how we get the solutions. In the first equation, <m>x</m> is squared, so we perform the opposite operation to solve, or take the square root of both sides:
  <md><mrow>\sqrt{x^2} \amp = \pm \sqrt{25}</mrow>
      <mrow> x \amp = \pm 5</mrow></md></p>

<p>In the second equation, <m>x</m> is an exponent. We ask ourselves "What power do we need on base 2 to get 8?" Finding a power is called taking a logarithm.
    <md><mrow>\log_2 {2^x} \amp = \log_2{8}</mrow>
      <mrow> x \amp = 3</mrow></md></p></task>

<task><p>Now compare the two equations below. One is cubic and one is exponential:
    <me>~~~~\text{(1)}~~~x^3 = 17 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\text{(2)}~~~10^x = 135</me> 
These are not so easy to solve in your head. But we use the same techniques as before:                                    
    <me>~~~~\sqrt[3]{x^3} = \sqrt[3]{17} ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\log_{10}{10^x} = \log_{10}{135}</me>                 
But this time, we use a calculator to evaluate the answers. Locate the log button on your calculator.
    <me>~~~~~x = ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~x = </me>                               
The solution of the first equation answers the question "What number must I cube to get 17?" The solution of the second equation answers the question "To what power must I raise 10 to get 135?"</p></task>
</activity>

<activity><title>Definition of Logarithm</title>
<introduction><p>We use logarithms to solve exponential equations.</p>  

  <p><m>\log_b {x}</m>  means "to what power must I raise <m>b</m> to get <m>x</m>?"</p>

<p>For example, <m>~\log_4 {64} = \alert{3}~</m>  because  <m>~4^\alert{3} = 64</m></p></introduction>
