<activity><title>Logarithms and Inverse Operations</title>
<introduction><p>We use inverse operations to solve equations. For example, cubing and taking cube roots are inverse operations. Each operation undoes the effect of the other.  Start with any number, say 5, cube it, and then take the cube root. We get back to the original number:                     
  <me>5 \rightarrow \text{cube} \rightarrow 5^3 = 125 \rightarrow \text{take cube root} \rightarrow \sqrt[3]{125} = 5</me>              

We can write the two operations in one step, like this:  <m>~~\sqrt[3]{5^3} = 5~~</m>. The same thing works for any number <m>x</m>, so <m>~~\sqrt[3]{x^3} = x~~</m>.</p></introduction>    

