    <li><p><m>(\sqrt{5936})^2 = <fillin/></m></p></li>
    <li><p><m>\dfrac{1}{1/6.97} = <fillin/></m></p></li>
  </ol></p></task>

<task><p>Logarithms and exponentials are inverse operations. Taking a logarithm base <m>b</m> is the opposite of evaluating an exponential function with base <m>b</m>. For example, let <m>b=3</m>, and start by start by evaluating <m>b^x</m> with <m>x=4</m>. Then take the log base 3 of the result:
    <me>x=\alert{4} \rightarrow \text{exponential function} \rightarrow 3^4 = 81 \rightarrow \text{logarithm} \rightarrow \log_3{81} = \alert{4}</me>
Or, <m>~\log_3 {3^4} = 4</m>.  So we have the rule:  <m>~\log_b {b^x} = x</m></p>

